<article>
    <h1>Head first into a new world</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200729/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-07-29"><time>2020-07-29</time></a>
        - <span>BIG PICTURE</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>A male joey popped his head out of his mother’s pouch to greet vis­i­tors yes­ter­day at the Sin­ga­pore Zoo.</p>
    <p>Born ear­lier this year on Feb 4, the joey is a Good­fel­low’s tree kan­ga­roo, one of the rarest an­i­mals in zoos around the world.</p>
    <p>With the ar­rival of this mi­nus­cule mar­su­pial, the global pop­u­la­tion of this species un­der hu­man care now stands at just 58.</p>
    <p>The yet-to-be-named joey was born to first-time par­ents Makaia and Nu­pela (left).</p>
    <p>As with all mar­su­pi­als, tree kan­ga­roos are born in an al­most em­bry­onic state af­ter a ges­ta­tion pe­riod of about 40 days.</p>
    <p>The jelly­bean-sized new­born has to make an ar­du­ous crawl into the mother’s pouch, where the rest of his devel­op­ment takes place. Only about eight months later will the joey emerge from the pouch com­pletely and take his first steps.</p>
    <p>Nu­pela’s ded­i­cated care team at the zoo wit­nessed the birth and the joey’s crawl into his mother’s pouch.</p>
    <p>The bond and trust between mum and her keep­ers al­low daily checks on Nu­pela’s pouch to mon­i­tor the baby’s growth and record sig­nif­i­cant de­vel­op­ments.</p>

